### Component

Forge

### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?

- [ ] Foundry
- [X] Foundryup

### What version of Foundry are you on?

forge 0.2.0 (721093d 2022-04-05T00:10:42.550532+00:00)

### What command(s) is the bug in?

forge test

### Operating System

macOS (amd)

### Describe the bug

I have a couple of tests that I was using the fuzzer for. They all work except one that freezes in the test files compilation stage when i run `forge test`.
This is the code for the test:
```
function testPassUserGiveXp(uint256 amount) public {
        uint256 passId = pass.newPass(1, 1, bundlesArray[0]);
        vm.prank(oracle);
        pass.giveXp(passId, amount, address(this));
        (uint256 userXp, bool prem) = pass.userInfo(address(this), passId);
        assertEq(userXp, amount);
    }
```
I've run `forge clean`, `foundryup`. It works if I remove the `uint amount` argument from the function. 
It stays on this screen for at least 4-5 mins after which I just cancelled it. 

This is the function against which I'm testing it.
```
function giveXp(
        uint256 _passId,
        uint256 _xp,
        address _recipient
    ) external {
        if (!hasRole(ORACLE_ROLE, _msgSender())) {
            revert OnlyOracleCanGiveXp({sender: _msgSender()});
        }

        uint256 oldLevel = level(_recipient, _passId);
        unchecked {
            userInfo[_recipient][_passId].xp += _xp;
        }
        uint256 newLevel = level(_recipient, _passId);
        if (oldLevel != newLevel) {
            emit LevelUp(_recipient, _passId, oldLevel, newLevel);
        }
    }
```
I don't think I missed anything here, any help would be appreciated, thanks.
<img width="1011" alt="Screen Shot 2022-04-04 at 10 50 36 PM" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26520682/161687376-98aa9c00-5fbd-470c-ba25-d70df996e6a0.png">

I found the reason for the freeze. The level function is:
```
function level(address _user, uint256 _passId) public view returns (uint256 level_) {
        level_ = 1;
        uint256 currentXP = userInfo[_user][_passId].xp;
        while (true) {
            uint256 xpToNext = xpFormula[_passId][0] * (level_**xpFormula[_passId][1]);
            if (xpToNext > currentXP) break;
            currentXP -= xpToNext;
            level_++;
        }
    }
```
vm.assume(amount < 100_000_000): 935.43ms
vm.assume(amount < 100_000_000_0): 1.83s
vm.assume(amount < 100_000_000_00): 3.86s
vm.assume(amount < 100_000_000_000): 8.75s

I can't even imagine how long it'll take to compute with a value close to 2^256, so it wasn't really an error at all. Thanks for your time and sorry for the false alarm!
